This comes just two days before Sukumaran's mother and sister tearfully pleaded for him to be spared after they received official word he and Andrew Chan will be executed this month.

It comes after the Australian drug smugglers had their second bid for clemency officially rejected on Wednesday, dashing their final hope of avoiding the firing squad.

For two weeks, the families of Sukumaran and his co-ringleader in the 2005 Bali Nine plot, Chan, have walked silently in and out of Kerobokan jail for twice-daily visiting hours.

Australia's consul-general Majel Hind brought confirmation from Indonesian authorities on Friday that the execution will be carried out within three weeks. 

